Great, let's walk through a simple example of streaming using Node.js (backend) and Fetch API (frontend).

---

## 🧠 Backend (Node.js with Express)

```js
import express from "express";

const app = express();

app.get("/stream", (req, res) => {
  res.setHeader("Content-Type", "text/plain");
  res.setHeader("Transfer-Encoding", "chunked");

  let count = 0;
  const interval = setInterval(() => {
    count++;
    res.write(`Chunk ${count}\n`);

    if (count === 5) {
      clearInterval(interval);
      res.end("\nDone streaming!");
    }
  }, 1000);
});

app.listen(3000, () => console.log("Server running on port 3000"));
```

---

## 🌐 Frontend (Fetch Streaming)

```js
async function fetchStream() {
  const response = await fetch("http://localhost:3000/stream");
  const reader = response.body.getReader();
  const decoder = new TextDecoder();

  let result = "";

  while (true) {
    const { done, value } = await reader.read();
    if (done) break;

    const chunk = decoder.decode(value);
    result += chunk;

    console.log("Received chunk:", chunk);
  }

  console.log("Final result:", result);
}

fetchStream();
```

---

## 🚀 How This Maps to Chat UI

In your chat UI:
- You create a message with `status: "streaming"`
- Append chunks as they arrive
- Mark it as `completed` when done

This approach is exactly how modern AI chat apps (like ChatGPT, Claude, etc.) work under the hood.

